---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  pageHeading="Network Architecture"
  description="How I'm designing the KC mesh: four backbone routers + client density. Simple concept, hobbyist-achievable execution."
  heroVariant="compact"
>
  <!-- Intro -->
  <section class="prose prose-lg dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
    <h2 class="text-4xl font-semibold leading-tight text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">
      How the KC mesh works
    </h2>
    <p class="text-xl text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
      This isn't complicated. Four backbone routers at cardinal points provide long-range coverage. Client nodes fill in local density. Messages hop between nodes to reach their destination.
    </p>
    <p class="text-xl text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
      That's it. No centralized servers, no infrastructure beyond what we deploy ourselves.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Basic Concept -->
  <section class="mt-12 rounded-3xl border-2 border-kc-blue/30 bg-gradient-to-br from-kc-blue/5 to-kc-sky/10 p-6 sm:p-8 dark:border-kc-sky/20 dark:from-kc-blue/10">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">The basic idea</h2>
    <div class="mt-6 space-y-4 text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
      <p><strong>1. Backbone routers</strong> stay in one place, run 24/7, and provide long-range coverage from elevated locations.</p>
      <p><strong>2. Client nodes</strong> are mobile or fixed devices people run for personal use. They also relay messages for others.</p>
      <p><strong>3. Messages hop</strong> between nodes (up to 3 hops by default) to reach destinations beyond direct range.</p>
      <p><strong>4. No central server</strong> required for mesh operation. MQTT gateway (optional) bridges to internet for monitoring/integration.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Four-Router Strategy -->
  <section class="mt-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Four-router backbone strategy</h2>
    <div class="mt-6 prose prose-lg dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <p>
        The plan is simple: deploy one backbone router in each cardinal direction (east, west, north, south). These provide the long-range coverage skeleton. Client nodes fill in the gaps.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-6 grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2">
      <article class="rounded-3xl border-2 border-mesh-green/30 bg-mesh-green/5 p-6 dark:border-mesh-green/20 dark:bg-mesh-green/10">
        <div class="flex items-center justify-between">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-mesh-green">Router 1: East Side</h3>
          <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 rounded-full bg-mesh-green px-2.5 py-1 text-xs font-semibold text-ink-900">
            <span class="block w-2 h-2 rounded-full bg-ink-900 animate-pulse"></span>
            LIVE
          </span>
        </div>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <li>• Covers east KC, Raytown direction</li>
          <li>• 15-foot elevation, ~5-8 mile coverage</li>
          <li>• Router + MQTT gateway role</li>
          <li>• Solar powered, runs 24/7</li>
        </ul>
      </article>

      <article class="rounded-3xl border-2 border-kc-red/30 bg-gradient-to-br from-kc-red/5 to-sunset-amber/5 p-6 dark:border-sunset-amber/20 dark:from-kc-red/10">
        <div class="flex items-center justify-between">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-kc-red dark:text-sunset-amber">Router 2: West Side</h3>
          <span class="inline-flex items-center rounded-full bg-kc-red px-2.5 py-1 text-xs font-semibold text-cream-50 dark:bg-sunset-amber dark:text-ink-900">
            PRIORITY
          </span>
        </div>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <li>• Target: Johnson County / west KC</li>
          <li>• Closes critical coverage gap</li>
          <li>• Seeking host site with elevation</li>
          <li>• Enables east-west metro backbone</li>
        </ul>
      </article>

      <article class="rounded-3xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-6 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <div class="flex items-center justify-between">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Router 3: North Metro</h3>
          <span class="inline-flex items-center rounded-full border border-border-light bg-surface-200 px-2.5 py-1 text-xs font-semibold text-ink-700 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-800 dark:text-cream-100">
            PLANNED
          </span>
        </div>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <li>• Target: Northland area</li>
          <li>• River crossing coverage</li>
          <li>• After Router 2 deployment</li>
        </ul>
      </article>

      <article class="rounded-3xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-6 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <div class="flex items-center justify-between">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Router 4: South Metro</h3>
          <span class="inline-flex items-center rounded-full border border-border-light bg-surface-200 px-2.5 py-1 text-xs font-semibold text-ink-700 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-800 dark:text-cream-100">
            PLANNED
          </span>
        </div>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <li>• Target: South KC metro</li>
          <li>• Completes cardinal coverage</li>
          <li>• After Routers 2 & 3</li>
        </ul>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- How Messages Route -->
  <section class="mt-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">How messages actually route</h2>
    <div class="mt-6 prose prose-lg dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <p>
        Meshtastic uses flood routing. When you send a message, your node broadcasts it. Every node that hears it rebroadcasts it (up to the hop limit). Eventually it reaches the destination.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>It's not efficient, but it's simple and it works.</strong> No routing tables to maintain, no central coordination needed. Just radios talking to each other.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-6 space-y-4">
      <details class="group rounded-2xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-5 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <summary class="cursor-pointer text-base font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Example: Message from east side to west side (once Router 2 is deployed)</summary>
        <div class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <p><strong>Step 1:</strong> You send a message from east KC. Your client node broadcasts it.</p>
          <p><strong>Step 2:</strong> Router 1 hears it, rebroadcasts it (hop 1).</p>
          <p><strong>Step 3:</strong> Router 2 (west side) or intermediate client nodes hear it, rebroadcast (hop 2).</p>
          <p><strong>Step 4:</strong> Destination client node on west side receives it.</p>
          <p>Total hops: 2-3. Well within the default limit of 3.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-2xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-5 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <summary class="cursor-pointer text-base font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">What happens when hop limit is reached</summary>
        <div class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <p>Each message has a hop counter. Every time a node rebroadcasts it, the counter increments.</p>
          <p>When it hits the hop limit (default 3), nodes stop rebroadcasting it. Message dies there.</p>
          <p>This prevents infinite loops and keeps network traffic manageable.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-2xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-5 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
        <summary class="cursor-pointer text-base font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Why routers improve this</summary>
        <div class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
          <p>Routers are always on, always listening. They don't sleep to save battery like client nodes might.</p>
          <p>They're deployed at elevation, so they can hear and reach more nodes.</p>
          <p>This means messages are more likely to successfully hop across the network even when client node density is low.</p>
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- MQTT Gateway Role -->
  <section class="mt-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">MQTT gateway (optional internet bridge)</h2>
    <div class="mt-6 prose prose-lg dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <p>
        <strong>The mesh works fine without internet.</strong> That's the whole point—off-grid communications.
      </p>
      <p>
        But Router 1 also runs an MQTT gateway, which bridges the mesh to the internet. This allows:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Remote monitoring of network health</li>
        <li>Connection to other distant mesh networks via MQTT</li>
        <li>Web dashboard integration (future)</li>
        <li>Data logging and analysis</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        <strong>Most nodes don't need to be gateways.</strong> One or two per network is enough. Router 1 handles this for KC.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-6 rounded-xl bg-kc-red/10 border border-kc-red/30 p-5 dark:bg-sunset-amber/10 dark:border-sunset-amber/30">
      <p class="text-sm text-ink-700 dark:text-cream-100">
        <strong>Security note:</strong> Router 1's MQTT gateway uses encryption. Local mesh traffic isn't exposed to public MQTT. If you run a gateway, use encryption keys and understand what you're bridging.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Prosumer Scale -->
  <section class="mt-12 rounded-3xl border border-border-light bg-surface-100 p-6 sm:p-8 dark:border-border-dark dark:bg-sand-900">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink-900 dark:text-cream-50">Why this works at hobbyist scale</h2>
    <div class="mt-6 prose prose-lg dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <p>
        <strong>This isn't commercial infrastructure.</strong> It's four routers running on solar panels and consumer-grade hardware. Total investment: maybe $500-800 for all four routers.
      </p>
      <p>
        Compare that to what it would cost to build commercial coverage: tens of thousands for sites, licensing, professional equipment, maintenance contracts.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Hobbyist-grade is good enough.</strong> We don't need 99.999% uptime. We need backup communications that work when cell towers don't. This achieves that goal at a price point where one person can fund and deploy it.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Get Involved -->
  <section class="mt-12 text-center">
    <div class="inline-block rounded-3xl bg-gradient-to-br from-kc-blue to-kc-red p-8 text-cream-50 shadow-card md:p-10">
      <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold">Help build this infrastructure</h3>
      <p class="mt-3 max-w-xl text-base opacity-95">
        Deploy a client node to add density. Or help find a west-side site for Router 2.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-6 flex flex-wrap justify-center gap-4">
        <a
          href="/get-started/join"
          class="inline-flex items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-cream-50 px-6 py-2.5 text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-kc-blue transition hover:bg-surface-200"
        >
          Join the Mesh
        </a>
        <a
          href="/guides/west-side"
          class="inline-flex items-center justify-center rounded-full border border-cream-50 px-6 py-2.5 text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-cream-50 transition hover:bg-cream-50 hover:text-kc-blue"
        >
          Host Router 2
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
